<!-- FAQ -->
<section class="content-section">
  <div class="container">
    <div class="section-header">
      <span class="section-label">FAQ</span>
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <p>Common questions about electrical panel upgrades in Utah.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="faq-list">
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>How much does an electrical panel upgrade cost in Utah?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>An electrical panel upgrade in Utah typically costs between $1,500 and $4,000 for a standard 200-amp panel replacement. Costs vary based on panel size, permit fees, whether the meter base needs replacement, and the condition of existing wiring. Call <a href="tel:801-885-4521">801-885-4521</a> for a free estimate. See our <a href="/guides/electrical-panel-upgrade-cost-utah/">detailed cost guide</a> for more information.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>When do I need to upgrade from 100 amps to 200 amps?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>You should upgrade to 200 amps if you are adding an EV charger, hot tub, or major appliances; if your breakers trip frequently; if you are planning a home addition or remodel; or if your home still has a fuse box. Most modern Utah homes require 200 amps to safely handle current electrical loads.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>Do I need a permit for a panel upgrade in Utah?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>Yes. Electrical panel upgrades require a permit in all Utah municipalities. The permit ensures the work is inspected and meets current electrical codes. Osborne Electric handles the entire permit process, including application, scheduling inspections, and ensuring the installation passes on the first inspection.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>What is a subpanel and do I need one?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>A subpanel is a secondary electrical panel that distributes power to a specific area of your home, such as a garage, workshop, or addition. Subpanels are useful when your main panel is full or when you need circuits in an area far from the main panel. Osborne Electric installs subpanels rated from 60 to 125 amps depending on your needs.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>Can I upgrade my panel to support an EV charger?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>Yes. Most Level 2 EV chargers require a dedicated 240-volt, 40 to 50-amp circuit. If your current panel does not have capacity for this circuit, a panel upgrade or subpanel installation will be needed. Osborne Electric handles the full process from panel assessment through charger circuit installation.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
      <details class="faq-details">
        <summary>How long does a panel upgrade take?</summary>
        <div class="faq-details-body">
          <p>Most residential panel upgrades are completed in a single day. A standard 100-amp to 200-amp upgrade typically involves replacing the panel, updating the meter base if required, and reconnecting all circuits. Your power will be off for a portion of the day while the work is performed.</p>
        </div>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

